data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has three patterns that need migration:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---------|----------|-------------|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort** | Keeps thread alive after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` to decide whether to continue |
| **Thread.Abort in Stop()** | Force-kills worker | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` — no force-kill equivalent |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime — your `Stop()` method will crash. `ThreadAbortException` will never be thrown, so your rollback logic becomes dead code.

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work — migrated from ThreadAbortException catch
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed. Loop condition will exit naturally.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish cleanly
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't exit in time. With cooperative cancellation,
                // this means GetNextItem or ProcessItem isn't responding
                // to the token. Fix those methods — there is no force-kill
                // equivalent in modern .NET.
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

---

### Critical: You must update `GetNextItem`

The original `Thread.Abort` could interrupt a blocking `GetNextItem()` mid-wait. Cooperative cancellation **cannot** — the method must check the token itself. If it blocks on a queue:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Dequeue(); // blocks if empty
}

// AFTER — responds to cancellation
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // BlockingCollection<T>.Take accepts a token natively
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException

    // Or if using Thread.Sleep to poll:
    // Replace Thread.Sleep(ms) with token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)
}
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **`GetNextItem` still blocks** | If this method does synchronous I/O or `WaitOne()` without the token, cancellation stalls indefinitely. Every blocking call in the chain must accept the token. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` ignores tokens** | Replace `Thread.Sleep(ms)` with `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` anywhere in the call chain. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones. Without it you'd mask bugs. |
| **Leaking `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — the new `Dispose()` method handles this. Always call `Stop()`/`Dispose()` on shutdown. |
| **Assuming cancellation is instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort` (which injected an exception immediately), cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` inside `ProcessItem` if it's long-running. |
